Environment-climate: for a European New Deal
BRUXELLES – In Brussels and in European capitals, the "Green New Deal" is on everyone's lips, echoing the visionary economic program launched by President Franklin D. Roosevelt in 1933.
But this time, it is about the environment and climate.
And Europe is the continent where we can and must act.
The European Union's commitment to these issues is not new: we have a common program since 1972.
Later in 2005, the EU established the first emissions trading system, which remains the world's first CO2 market.
And in 2015, the EU played a leading role in negotiating the Paris Agreement, committing to reduce its own greenhouse gas emissions by 40% (base: 1990 levels).
But these measures, although significant, are not sufficient to address the challenges facing the world today.
Increasing temperatures could lead to the complete disappearance of Arctic ice by 2050.
Bees and many other insects are dying out, while microplastic pollution is ubiquitous in our environment.
And the number of people suffering from respiratory diseases is increasing as air pollution worsens.
We nevertheless have reasons to remain optimistic.
Let us look at these people, growing in number every day, willing to take action to question their lifestyles. Like these students and entire families taking to the streets of Stockholm, Prague, Brussels, and Milan every Thursday!
Companies are also committing, seeing the unmatched economic potential of a green economy.
But it is the policymakers and politicians, at the national and European levels, who too often lack ambition.
We have a window of opportunity to act. Seize it!
And let's make a green Europe our top political priority for the years to come, focused on three key areas.
Firstly, Europe must become a carbon-neutral economy by 2050.
If we want to limit global warming to 1.5°C, we have no other choice: the EU's net carbon dioxide emissions must be reduced to zero by mid-century.
Together, we can invest heavily in the future of our mobility, energy-efficient buildings, and renewable energy, as well as in key technologies such as hydrogen batteries, next-generation solar panels, and green chemistry.
We must also apply strict CO2 emission limits to new private cars, public transport, as well as maritime and air commercial transport.
And, by working closely with our automotive industry, we can make Europe the first continent of electric vehicles by 2030.
Secondly, Europe must play a leading role in the responsible use of resources and become a true circular economy that is waste-efficient.
Every year, 8 billion tons of materials are transformed into energy or products in the European Union.
But only 0.6 billion tons come from recycling.
We need to do much better, which will require focusing on four areas: food waste and the bioeconomy, textiles, construction, and rapidly evolving consumer goods.
Let's get to work today, by launching for example an European initiative to combat planned obsolescence of household appliances and electronic devices, and by eliminating plastics from our value chains.
Thirdly, we must do much more to protect biodiversity.
According to the WWF, wild species populations have decreased by about 60% worldwide since 1970.
The UN Biodiversity Conference, which will take place in Beijing next year, will be decisive.
Once again, the EU must lead the way.
We must strengthen EU legislation on species protection and put forward an ambitious plan for the blue economy and the preservation of our seas.
We must also launch a real debate with our farmers (not against them!) on revising our standards and modernizing the Common Agricultural Policy to support this green transition.
But these massive challenges that await us, we will not be able to accomplish if it is always the same – and the most vulnerable – who are asked to bear the costs.
All measures under consideration must therefore first and foremost be designed to minimize social costs.
And in parallel, we must today work with our partners for international cooperation, fighting against unfair competition.
For it is useless to have strict European rules on pesticides or forest management if our imported food and timber are produced without respecting sustainability criteria.
These three initiatives could become the pillars of a Sustainability Pact at the heart of the EU's new political cycle.
For we are in a situation of acute ecological debt, and it would be more than justified that the stability and growth pact applying to the public finances of the member states finds an equivalent for the objectives of a green Europe!
To achieve its goals, this Sustainability Pact will require coordinated action in all areas: climate, trade, taxation, agriculture, and innovation.
The EU should not hesitate to use its regulatory powers, for example: expanding the scope of legislation on eco-design and the "extended producer responsibility" for products placed on the market could significantly stimulate innovation in favor of the environment.
Massive investments will also be necessary.
The European Commission estimates that the EU will need an additional 180 billion euros in investments each year to meet the commitments made under the Paris Agreement.
This is an achievable goal.
The European Investment Bank is already the largest multilateral actor providing climate-focused funding.
The EU's new budget and its investment plan, making the best use of private sector investments, could still further enhance the Union's action power.
The financial sector will have to play a fundamental role: through the disclosure of climate-related financial information, we can encourage the world's largest financial institutions, such as the Norwegian sovereign fund and BlackRock, to adopt a long-term vision and avoid what Governor of the Bank of England Mark Carney called the "tragedy of the horizon."
Finally, although some member states may see this as a risky project, we must have a debate on taxation, as well as on subsidies applicable to fossil fuels. In short, on the integration of sustainability into public spending.
Beyond these projects, these initiatives, the key lies in the approach. For this "Green New Deal" to bear fruit, we must set ambitious goals and "missions" for the short and long term that have real societal resonance.
With the member states and the European Parliament, we will have to determine a common roadmap and conduct in-depth discussions, just as we do with our regions, cities, businesses, unions, and civil society.
All of this cannot be done overnight.
But we can no longer close our eyes and hold our breath to escape the reality of our environment.
It is already very late to launch a "Green New Deal" in Europe. But it is not too late.
Don't miss this new opportunity!
